/**
 * JUnit 5 / Mockito unit tests for the REFACTORED
 * {@link VerificationProviderServiceImpl}.
 *
 * <h3>What changed in the refactored code</h3>
 * <ul>
 *   <li>{@code selectSupplier()} now delegates to
 *       {@link WeightedSupplierSelector#select(List)} instead of
 *       iterating on {@code attempts < totalAttempts}.</li>
 *   <li>{@code updatePvAttempts()} is no longer called from
 *       {@code selectSupplier()}.  No DB UPDATE, no row lock.</li>
 *   <li>{@code OtpAttemptConfigService.callingOTP()} is never called
 *       during normal supplier selection.</li>
 *   <li>{@code OtpAttemptConfigService.reset()} is never called
 *       during normal supplier selection.</li>
 * </ul>
 *
 * <h3>Test design rationale</h3>
 * <ul>
 *   <li>All five {@code @Autowired} services are injected as Mockito mocks
 *       via {@code @InjectMocks}. No Spring context, no Oracle, no WebSphere.</li>
 *   <li>{@code CustomLogger} calls are fire-and-forget; Log4j degrades
 *       gracefully without a config file in test scope.</li>
 *   <li>{@code Utils.getEnvironmentWithoutDot()} is a static call inside
 *       {@code selectSupplierForInf()}. We stub
 *       {@code refSponsorConfigurationService.getConfigRecord()} to return
 *       {@code null}, which skips the non-prod override block entirely —
 *       the correct behaviour for all unit tests.</li>
 *   <li>For every test that exercises the INF path,
 *       {@code rpInfPvAttemptConfigService.getByProofingLevel()} must also
 *       be stubbed because {@code isSwitchingInfSupplierConfigured()} is
 *       called before the sorted query.</li>
 * </ul>
 *
 * Naming convention: methodName_shouldExpectedBehavior_whenCondition()
 */
